adopts an extensive periodization to identify the undeniable changes caused by industrialization and the persistence of pre-existing features and dynamics. The contributions range from the late Middle Ages to the 1990s and deepen historical characteristics of urban metabolism, the study of energy systems and their transitions, and the management and control of water resources. These reveal the strategies societies and states adopted to transform and adapt their surrounding environment in a constant and challenging equilibrium of diverse interests, whose impact over time has had environmental consequences on a global scale.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aAnthropozän. 4aEnergie. 4aTechnologie. 4aUmweltgeschichte.1 aBonan, Giacomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonan, Giacomo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDi Tullio, Matteo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentilcore, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraber, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirchhof, Astrid Mignon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoshelev, Yaroslav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenzini, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManthey, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeill, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Simone M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOcchi, Katia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOcchi, Katia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re